<comment datatype='string'>Both promoters &lt;i&gt;cfa&lt;/i&gt;p2 (&amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;38&lt;/sup&gt;) and &lt;i&gt;cfa&lt;/i&gt;p1 (&amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;38&lt;/sup&gt; and &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt;) are induced in response to neutral acetate [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16420371&quot;&gt;Rosenthal06&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18331469&quot;&gt;Rosenthal08&lt;/a&gt;], and they do not need accessory elements (activators or repressors), which suggests that acetate works directly with RNA polymerase in the transcription complex. The general responses to acetate of the two RNA polymerase forms were clearly different; &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;70&lt;/sup&gt; promoters responded with wide differences, but &amp;sigma;&lt;sup&gt;38&lt;/sup&gt; promoters were generally activated [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18331469&quot;&gt;Rosenthal08&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
 &lt;i&gt;cfa&lt;/i&gt; transcription is also induced by acidic and osmotic stress [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11244055&quot;&gt;Arnold01&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15716429&quot;&gt;Weber05&lt;/a&gt;]. &lt;i&gt;cfa&lt;/i&gt;p1 contains a perfect 14-bp inverted repeat with two half-site elements that read 5'-TTTTGTT-3', centered at position -40. No information concerning this inverted repeat is available, since it does not align with any known regulator-binding sites [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18331469&quot;&gt;Rosenthal08&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
